Package com.pulumiverse.vercel

Class DnsRecord

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.pulumi.resources.Resource
      • com.pulumi.resources.CustomResource
        • com.pulumiverse.vercel.DnsRecord
  • public class DnsRecord
extends com.pulumi.resources.CustomResource
    Provides a DNS Record resource. DNS records are instructions that live in authoritative DNS servers and provide information about a domain. > The `value` field must be specified on all DNS record types except `SRV`. When using `SRV` DNS records, the `srv` field must be specified. For more detailed information, please see the [Vercel documentation](https://vercel.com/docs/concepts/projects/custom-domains#dns-records) ## Example Usage 
     
 package generated_program;
 
 import com.pulumi.Context;
 import com.pulumi.Pulumi;
 import com.pulumi.core.Output;
 import com.pulumiverse.vercel.DnsRecord;
 import com.pulumiverse.vercel.DnsRecordArgs;
 import com.pulumi.vercel.inputs.DnsRecordSrvArgs;
 import java.util.List;
 import java.util.ArrayList;
 import java.util.Map;
 import java.io.File;
 import java.nio.file.Files;
 import java.nio.file.Paths;
 
 public class App {
     public static void main(String[] args) {
         Pulumi.run(App::stack);
     }
 
     public static void stack(Context ctx) {
         var a = new DnsRecord("a", DnsRecordArgs.builder()
             .domain("example.com")
             .name("subdomain")
             .type("A")
             .ttl(60)
             .value("192.168.0.1")
             .build());
 
         var aaaa = new DnsRecord("aaaa", DnsRecordArgs.builder()
             .domain("example.com")
             .name("subdomain")
             .type("AAAA")
             .ttl(60)
             .value("::0")
             .build());
 
         var alias = new DnsRecord("alias", DnsRecordArgs.builder()
             .domain("example.com")
             .name("subdomain")
             .type("ALIAS")
             .ttl(60)
             .value("example2.com.")
             .build());
 
         var caa = new DnsRecord("caa", DnsRecordArgs.builder()
             .domain("example.com")
             .name("subdomain")
             .type("CAA")
             .ttl(60)
             .value("1 issue \"letsencrypt.org\"")
             .build());
 
         var cname = new DnsRecord("cname", DnsRecordArgs.builder()
             .domain("example.com")
             .name("subdomain")
             .type("CNAME")
             .ttl(60)
             .value("example2.com.")
             .build());
 
         var mx = new DnsRecord("mx", DnsRecordArgs.builder()
             .domain("example.com")
             .name("subdomain")
             .type("MX")
             .ttl(60)
             .mxPriority(333)
             .value("example2.com.")
             .build());
 
         var srv = new DnsRecord("srv", DnsRecordArgs.builder()
             .domain("example.com")
             .name("subdomain")
             .type("SRV")
             .ttl(60)
             .srv(DnsRecordSrvArgs.builder()
                 .port(6000)
                 .weight(60)
                 .priority(127)
                 .target("example2.com.")
                 .build())
             .build());
 
         var txt = new DnsRecord("txt", DnsRecordArgs.builder()
             .domain("example.com")
             .name("subdomain")
             .type("TXT")
             .ttl(60)
             .value("some text value")
             .build());
 
     }
 }
    ## Import If importing into a personal account, or with a team configured on the provider, simply use the record id. - record_id can be taken from the network tab inside developer tools, while you are on the domains page, or can be queried from the Vercel API directly (https://vercel.com/docs/rest-api/endpoints/dns#list-existing-dns-records). ```sh $ pulumi import vercel:index/dnsRecord:DnsRecord example rec_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx ``` Alternatively, you can import via the team_id and record_id. - team_id can be found in the team `settings` tab in the Vercel UI. - record_id can be taken from the network tab inside developer tools, while you are on the domains page, or can be queried from the Vercel API directly (https://vercel.com/docs/rest-api/endpoints/dns#list-existing-dns-records). ```sh $ pulumi import vercel:index/dnsRecord:DnsRecord example team_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx/rec_xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx ```

      • value

        public com.pulumi.core.Output<java.util.Optional<java.lang.String>> value()
        Returns:
        The value of the DNS record. The format depends on the 'type' property. For an 'A' record, this should be a valid IPv4 address. For an 'AAAA' record, this should be an IPv6 address. For 'ALIAS' records, this should be a hostname. For 'CAA' records, this should specify specify which Certificate Authorities (CAs) are allowed to issue certificates for the domain. For 'CNAME' records, this should be a different domain name. For 'MX' records, this should specify the mail server responsible for accepting messages on behalf of the domain name. For 'TXT' records, this can contain arbitrary text.
